text_clean: Joby Aviation Inc (JOBY) shares fell 4.2% to close at $13.93 on Friday, January 24, 2026, as the Russell 2000 index declined 1.8% while the S&P 500 and Nasdaq posted modest gains. Archer Aviation, another electric air-taxi company, fell approximately 4.4% on the same day. Joby is developing an electric vertical take-off and landing (eVTOL) aircraft for air-taxi services, and the chairman of Dubai’s Roads and Transport Authority announced that commercial operations using Joby’s aircraft are expected to begin by the end of 2026. A recent filing disclosed that Joby’s subsidiary agreed to purchase a 728,000-square-foot property in Vandalia, Ohio, for $61.5 million, with the transaction scheduled to close no later than February 27, 2026. CEO JoeBen Bevirt stated that the Ohio facility will support Joby’s near-term plan to double production and may enable significant future growth. As of November 5, 2025, Joby reported $978.1 million in cash, cash equivalents, and investments, and noted progress toward obtaining FAA Type Inspection Authorization, a certification phase involving flight testing by FAA pilots. The Federal Reserve is scheduled to hold its monetary policy meeting on January 27–28, 2026, with the policy statement and press conference set for January 28. Joby’s next earnings report is scheduled for February 25, 2026. Certification delays could increase manufacturing costs, and the company previously raised approximately $514 million through a discounted share offering in October 2025.
